# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: canton-ohio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:canton-ohio/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:canton-ohio/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:canton-ohio/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:canton-ohio/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:canton-ohio/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:canton-ohio/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:canton-ohio/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:canton-ohio/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:canton-ohio/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:canton-ohio/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The **1890 United States census** was taken beginning June 2, 1890.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The census determined the resident population of the United States to be 62,979,766, an increase of 25.5 percent over the 50,189,209 persons enumerated during the 1880 census.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The data reported that the distribution of the population had resulted in the disappearance of the American frontier.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a majority of states recorded populations of over one million and the first in which three cities, New York City, Chicago, and Philadelphia, recorded populations of over one million.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The census also saw Chicago rise in rank to the nation's second-most populous city, a position it would hold until Los Angeles, the 57th-most populous city as of 1890, supplanted it in 1990.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] This was the first U.S. census to use machines to tabulate the collected data.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] Most of the 1890 census materials were destroyed on January 10, 1921, when the Commerce Department building caught fire, and in the subsequent disposal of the remaining damaged records.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census was the first to be compiled using methods invented by Herman Hollerith and was overseen by Superintendents Robert P.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] Data was entered on a machine readable medium (punched cards) and tabulated by machine.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] Changes from the 1880 census included the larger population, the number of data items to be collected from individuals, the Census Bureau headcount, the volume of scheduled publications, and the use of Hollerith's electromechanical tabulators.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The net effect of these changes was to reduce the time required to process the census from eight years for the 1880 census to six years for the 1890 census.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The total population of 62,947,714, the family, or *rough*, count, was announced after only six weeks of processing (punched cards were not used for this tabulation).
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The public reaction to this tabulation was disbelief, as it was widely believed that the "right answer" was at least 75,000,000.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The United States census of 1890 showed a total of 248,253 Native Americans living in the United States, down from 400,764 Native Americans identified in the census of 1850.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census announced that the frontier region of the United States no longer existed, and that the Census Bureau would no longer track the westward migration of the U.S. population.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] In practice, however, said migration can still be tracked by plotting each succeeding census' mean center of United States population.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] By 1890, settlement in the American West had reached sufficient population density that the frontier line had disappeared.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The original data for the 1890 census is mostly unavailable.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The population schedules were damaged in a fire in the basement of the U.S.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] Department of Commerce building in Washington, D.C. in 1921.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] Some 25% of the materials were presumed destroyed and another 50% damaged by smoke and water, although the actual damage may have been closer to 15–25%.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The damage to the records led to an outcry for a permanent National Archives.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] In December 1932, following standard federal record-keeping procedures, the Chief Clerk of the Bureau of the Census sent the Librarian of Congress a list of papers to be destroyed, including the original 1890 census schedules.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] The Librarian was asked by the Bureau to identify any records which should be retained for historical purposes, but the Librarian did not accept the census records.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] Congress authorized destruction of that list of records on February 21, 1933, and the surviving original 1890 census records were destroyed by government order by 1934 or 1935.
[src:canton-ohio/1890-united-states-census] Few sets of microdata from the 1890 census survive.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 3, 1896.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Former Governor William McKinley, the Republican nominee, defeated former Representative William Jennings Bryan, the Democratic nominee.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1896 campaign, which took place during an economic depression known as the Panic of 1893, was a political realignment that ended the old Third Party System and began the Fourth Party System.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Democratic President Grover Cleveland did not seek election to a second consecutive term (which would have been his third overall), leaving the Democratic nomination open.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] An attorney and former congressman, Bryan galvanized support with his Cross of Gold speech, which called for reform of the monetary system and attacked business leaders as the cause of ongoing economic depression.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1896 Democratic National Convention repudiated the Cleveland administration and nominated Bryan on the fifth presidential ballot.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan then won the nomination of the Populist Party, which had won several states in 1892 and shared many of Bryan's policies.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In opposition to Bryan, some conservative Bourbon Democrats formed the National Democratic Party and nominated Senator John M.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McKinley prevailed by a wide margin on the first ballot at the 1896 Republican National Convention.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Since the onset of the Panic of 1893, the nation had been mired in a deep economic depression, marked by low prices, low profits, high unemployment, and violent strikes.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Economic issues, especially tariff policy and the question of whether the gold standard should be preserved for the money supply, were central issues.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McKinley forged a conservative coalition in which businessmen, professionals, prosperous farmers, and skilled factory workers turned off by Bryan's agrarian policies were heavily represented.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was strongest in cities and in the Northeast, Upper Midwest, and Pacific Coast.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Republican campaign manager Mark Hanna pioneered many modern campaign techniques, facilitated by a $3.5 million budget.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan presented his campaign as a crusade of the working man against the rich, who impoverished America by limiting the money supply.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He said that silver was in ample supply and if coined into money would restore prosperity while undermining the illicit power of the money trust.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan was strongest in the South, rural Midwest, and Rocky Mountain states.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His moralistic rhetoric and crusade for inflation (to be generated by the institution of bimetallism) alienated conservatives.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan campaigned vigorously throughout the swing states of the Midwest, while McKinley conducted a front porch campaign.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the end of an intensely heated contest, McKinley won a majority of the popular and electoral vote.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan won 46.7% of the popular vote and Palmer just under 1%.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Turnout was very high, passing 90% of the eligible voters in many places.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic Party's repudiation of its Bourbon faction largely gave Bryan and his supporters control of the party until the 1920s and set the stage for Republican domination of the Fourth Party System.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The four elections from 1884 to 1896 saw the incumbent party defeated each time; the only other such streak was from 1840 to 1852.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Louis, Missouri, held between June 16 and 18, 1896, the Republicans nominated William McKinley for president and New Jersey's Garret Hobart for vice president.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McKinley had just vacated the office of governor of Ohio.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both candidates were easily nominated on first ballots.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McKinley's campaign manager, the wealthy and talented Ohio businessman Mark Hanna, visited the leaders of large corporations and major, influential banks after the Republican Convention to raise funds for the campaign.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With many businessmen and bankers terrified of Bryan's populist rhetoric and demand for the end of the gold standard, Hanna had little difficulty raising record amounts of money.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He raised $3.5 million for the campaign and outspent the Democrats by an estimated 5-to-1 margin.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McKinley was the last veteran of the American Civil War to be nominated for president by either major party.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] One month after McKinley's nomination, supporters of silver-backed currency took control of the Democratic convention, held in Chicago on July 7–11.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Most of the Southern and Western delegates were committed to implementing the Populist Party's "free silver" ideas.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The convention repudiated Cleveland's gold standard policies and Cleveland himself.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This left the convention wide open: there was no obvious successor to Cleveland.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A two-thirds vote was required for the nomination and the silverites had it in spite of the extreme regional polarization of the delegates.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In a test vote on an anti-silver measure, the Eastern states (from Maryland to Maine), with 28% of the delegates, voted 96% in favor.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The other delegates voted 91% against, so the silverites could count on a majority of 67% of the delegates.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The attorney, former congressman, and unsuccessful Senate candidate William Jennings Bryan filled the void.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A superb orator, Bryan hailed from Nebraska and spoke for farmers suffering from the economic depression following the Panic of 1893.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the convention, he gave what has been considered one of the greatest political speeches in American history, the "Cross of Gold" Speech.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan presented a passionate defense of farmers and factory workers struggling to survive the economic depression, and attacked big-city business owners and leaders as the cause of much of their suffering.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He called for reform of the monetary system, an end to the gold standard, and government relief efforts for farmers and others hurt by the depression.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan's speech was so dramatic that many delegates carried him on their shoulders around the convention hall afterward.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The next day, eight names were placed in nomination: Richard Bland, William J.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan, Claude Matthews, Horace Boies, Joseph Blackburn, John R.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite a strong initial showing by Bland, who led on the first three ballots, Bryan's speech helped him gain the momentum required to win the nomination, which he did on the fifth ballot, after most of the other candidates withdrew in his favor.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After Bland's defeat, his supporters attempted to nominate him as Bryan's running mate, but Bland was more interested in winning back his former seat in the House of Representatives, and so withdrew his name from consideration despite leading the early rounds of voting.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Arthur Sewall, a wealthy shipbuilder from Maine, was eventually chosen as the vice-presidential nominee.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was felt that Sewall's wealth might encourage him to help pay some campaign expenses.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At just 36, Bryan was only a year older than required by the Constitution to be president.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He remains the youngest person ever nominated for president by a major party.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the several third parties active in 1896, by far the most prominent was the People's Party.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Formed in 1892, the Populists represented the philosophy of agrarianism (derived from Jeffersonian democracy), which held that farming was a superior way of life that was being exploited by bankers and middlemen.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Populists attracted cotton farmers in the South and wheat farmers in the West, but significantly few farmers in the Northeast and rural Midwest.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the presidential election of 1892, Populist candidate James B.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Weaver carried four states, and in 1894, the Populists scored victories in congressional and state legislature races in a number of Southern and Western states.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] By 1896, some Populists believed that they could replace the Democrats as the main opposition party to the Republicans.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, the Democrats' nomination of Bryan, who supported many Populist goals and ideas, placed the party in a dilemma.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Torn between choosing their own presidential candidate or supporting Bryan, the party leadership decided that nominating their own candidate would simply divide the forces of reform and hand the election to the more conservative Republicans.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At their national convention in 1896, the Populists chose Bryan as their presidential nominee.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, to demonstrate that they were still independent from the Democrats, the Populists also chose former Georgia Representative Thomas E.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Watson as their vice-presidential candidate instead of Arthur Sewall.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan eagerly accepted the Populist nomination, but was vague as to whether, if elected, he would choose Watson as his vice-president instead of Sewall.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With this election, the Populists began to be absorbed into the Democratic Party; within a few elections the party would disappear completely.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1896 election was particularly detrimental to the Populist Party in the South; the party divided itself between members who favored cooperation with the Democrats to achieve reform at the national level and members who favored cooperation with the Republicans to achieve reform at a state level.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan's Democratic and Populist supporters organized joint "fusion" tickets in several states with pledged electors drawn from both parties.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The *New York Times* counted seventy-one Populist and six Silver Republican electoral candidates pledged to Bryan.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In ten states where the fusion ticket was successful, twenty-seven electors voted for Bryan for president and Watson for vice president.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Prohibition Party went into the convention divided into two factions, each unwilling to give ground or compromise with the other.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The "Broad-Gauge" wing, led by Charles Bentley and former Kansas Governor John St.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John, demanded the inclusion of planks endorsing the free coinage of silver at 16:1 and of women's suffrage, the former refusing to accept the nomination if such amendments to the party platform were not approved.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The "Narrow-Gauge" wing, led by Samuel Dickie of Michigan and rallying around the candidacy of Joshua Levering, demanded that the party platform remain dedicated exclusively to the prohibition of alcohol.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Conflict between the two sides soon broke out over the nomination of a permanent chairman, with a number of presented candidates for the position withdrawing before Oliver Stewart of Illinois, a "Broad-Gauger", was nominated.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John supported the free coinage of silver, government control of railroads and telegraphs, an income tax and referendums, and was prevented from being tabled, giving "Broad-Gaugers" confidence, but a number of those who voted for the report were merely undecided or against gagging the report.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John's report was brought up to a formal vote the margins had largely reversed; it was rejected, 492 to 310.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With the silver delegates still in shock and St.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John attempting to move for a reconsideration, Illinois "Narrow-Gaugers" moved to offer as a substitute to both the minority and majority reports a single-plank platform centered on Prohibition.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A rising vote was taken in lieu of a roll call, with the "Narrow-Gauge" Platform winning the vote and being adopted.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In an attempt to mollify suffragists who were incensed at the lack of a plank endorsing women's suffrage, the plank itself was adopted through a resolution by the convention by a near unanimous vote.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] When it came to the nomination for president, many "Broad-Gaugers" were already openly considering bolting and running their own candidate as it became increasingly apparent that the "Narrow-Gaugers" had brought a majority of the convention under their influence.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Formal action was deferred until after the nomination for president was made.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Once Levering's nomination was confirmed without any visible opposition, around 200 of those who were suffragists, silverites or populists bolted the convention, led by Bentley and St.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John, and joined with the National Reform "Party" to create the National Party.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Afterward, the convention unanimously nominated Hale Johnson of Illinois for vice president.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Initially known as the "National Reform Party", the convention itself started only a day before the Prohibition National Convention, also being held in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Though initially only a gathering of eight or so delegates, it was hoped that any bolters from the Prohibition Party might find their way there and would support the nomination of Representative Joseph C.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A sizable bolt did indeed occur upon the nomination of Joshua Levering by the Prohibition Party to the presidency, with Charles E.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bentley and former Kansas governor John St.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John leading a walkout of "Broad-Gaugers" from their convention, St.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The delegates approved the minority report that had been rejected at the Prohibitionist Convention calling for free coinage and greenbacks, government control of railroads and telegraphs, direct election of senators and the president, and an income tax among others.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Socialist Labor Convention was held in New York City on July 9, 1896.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The convention nominated Charles Matchett of New York and Matthew Maguire of New Jersey.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Near the beginning of that year, U.S. senators from silver-producing states (Colorado, Idaho, Nevada, and Montana) began objecting to President Benjamin Harrison's economic policies and advocated the free coinage of silver.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Henry Teller notified the Senate that if the two major parties did not back down on their financial policies, the four western states would back a third party.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The *Portland Morning Oregonian* reported on June 27, 1892, that a Silver Party was being organized along those lines.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nevada silverites called a state convention to be held on June 5, 1892, just days following the close of the Democratic National Convention.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Francis Newlands was elected to the U.S.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Silverites took control of the legislature, assuring the election of William Stewart to the U.S.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The success of the Nevada silverites spurred their brethren in Colorado to action; the Colorado Silver Party never materialized, however.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the 1894 midterm elections, the Silver Party remained a Nevada party.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It swept all statewide offices, formerly held by Republicans.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John Edward Jones was elected Governor with 50% of the vote; Newlands was re-elected with 44%.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Following the Democratic Party debacle in 1894, James Weaver began agitating for the creation of a nationwide Silver Party.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He altered the People's Party platform from 1892 and eliminated planks he felt would be divisive for a larger party and began to lobby silver men around the nation.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The first major statement by the national Silver Party was an address delivered to the American Bimetallic League, printed in the Emporia Daily Gazette on March 6, 1895.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Letterhead for the nascent party promoted U.S.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Representative Joseph Sibley of Pennsylvania for president, noting that his endorsement by the Prohibitionists would secure that party's support.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Silver leaders met in Washington DC on January 22 to discuss holding a national convention.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They decided to wait until after the conventions of the two major parties in case one of them agreed to the 16:1 coinage demands.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Just a few days later, however, party regulars convinced the leaders to change course.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On January 29, the leaders issued a call for a national convention to be held in St.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mott, the Silver Party National Chairman, went to great lengths to organize state parties, but his efforts did not produce dramatic results.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Silver State convention in Ohio was attended by just 20 people, even though the president of the Bimetallic League, A.J.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although most Silverites had been pushing the nomination of Senator Teller, the situation changed with the Democratic nomination of William Jennings Bryan.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Congressman Newlands was in Chicago as the official Silver Party visitor, and he announced on July 10 that the Silver Party should endorse the Democratic ticket.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Louis making final arrangements for the Silver National Convention, told a reporter five days later "All the Silver Party wants is silver, and the Democratic platform will give us that." I.B.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 25, both Bryan and Arthur Sewall would be nominated by acclamation.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The pro-gold Democrats reacted to Bryan's nomination with a mixture of anger, desperation, and confusion.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A number of pro-gold Bourbon Democrats urged a "bolt" and the formation of a third party.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In response, a hastily arranged assembly on July 24 organized the National Democratic Party.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A follow-up meeting in August scheduled a nominating convention for September in Indianapolis and issued an appeal to fellow Democrats.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In this document, the National Democratic Party portrayed itself as the legitimate heir to Presidents Jefferson, Jackson, and Cleveland.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Delegates from forty-one states gathered at the National Democratic Party's national nominating convention in Indianapolis on September 2.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some delegates planned to nominate Cleveland, but they relented after a telegram arrived stating that he would not accept.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator William Freeman Vilas from Wisconsin, the main drafter of the National Democratic Party's platform, was a favorite of the delegates.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Vilas refused to run as the party's sacrificial lamb.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Palmer, a 79-year-old former senator from Illinois.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Simon Bolivar Buckner, a 73-year-old former governor of Kentucky, was nominated by acclamation for vice-president.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The ticket, symbolic of post-Civil War reconciliation, featured the oldest combined age of the candidates in American history.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite their advanced ages, Palmer and Buckner embarked on a busy speaking tour, including visits to most major cities in the East.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This won them considerable respect from the party faithful, although some found it hard to take the geriatric campaigning seriously.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] "You would laugh yourself sick could you see old Palmer," wrote lawyer Kenesaw Mountain Landis.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Palmer himself said at a campaign stop that if "this vast crowd casts its vote for William McKinley next Tuesday, I shall charge them with no sin." There was even some cooperation with the Republican Party, especially in finances.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republicans hoped that Palmer could draw enough Democratic votes from Bryan to tip marginal Midwestern and border states into McKinley's column.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In a private letter, Hewitt underscored the "entire harmony of action" between both parties in standing against Bryan.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, the National Democratic Party was not merely an adjunct to the McKinley campaign.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] An important goal was to nurture a loyal remnant for future victory.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Repeatedly they depicted Bryan's prospective defeat, and a credible showing for Palmer, as paving the way for ultimate recapture of the Democratic Party, and this did indeed happen in 1904.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Palmer-Buckner ticket remains the only third-party presidential campaign in history to have earned the endorsement of the *New York Times*.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While the Republican Party entered 1896 assuming that the Democrats were in shambles and victory would be easy, especially after the unprecedented Republican landslide in the congressional elections of 1894, the nationwide emotional response to the Bryan candidacy changed everything.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] By summer, it appeared that Bryan was ahead in the South and West and probably also in the Midwest.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan ran an aggressive campaign that appealed to lower-class Americans and evangelical Christians.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He traveled 18,000 miles by train and made around 600 speeches across the country.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He often displayed religious imagery at the site of his speeches.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The content of his speeches revolved around progressive policies such as the free coinage of silver and progressive tax reform that appealed to lower-class Americans.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the other hand, McKinley's campaign was much quieter and did not attempt to copy the populist rhetoric that Bryan relied on.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Bryan's rising popularity worried Republican campaign strategists.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] An entirely new strategy was called for by the McKinley campaign.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was designed to educate voters in the money issues, to demonstrate silverite fallacies, and to portray Bryan himself as a dangerous crusader.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McKinley would be portrayed as the safe and sound champion of jobs and sound money, with his high tariff proposals guaranteed to return prosperity for everyone.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The McKinley campaign would be national and centralized, using the Republican National Committee as the tool of the candidate, instead of the state parties' tool.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Furthermore, the McKinley campaign stressed his pluralistic commitment to prosperity for all groups (including minorities).
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The McKinley campaign invented a new form of campaign financing that has dominated American politics ever since.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Instead of asking office holders to return a cut of their pay, Hanna went to financiers and industrialists and made a business proposition.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He explained that Bryan would win if nothing happened, and that the McKinley team had a winning counterattack that would be very expensive.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He then would ask them how much it was worth to the business not to have Bryan as president.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He suggested an amount and was happy to take a check.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hanna had moved beyond partisanship and campaign rhetoric to a businessman's thinking about how to achieve a desired result.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Dawes to run his Chicago office and spend about $2 million in the critical region.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McKinley emulated Benjamin Harrison's 1888 front porch campaign and raised money from various interest and demographic groups from his home in Canton, Ohio.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His strategy involved inviting numerous interest and demographic group delegates to his house and giving a short speech to these groups.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His strategy led to McKinley earning enormous campaign funds, and he used this money to enlist 14,000 speakers to represent the McKinley campaign.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Meanwhile, traditional funders of the Democratic Party (mostly financiers from the Northeast) rejected Bryan, although he did manage to raise about $500,000.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some of it came from businessmen with interests in silver mining.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan never obtained the same amount of campaign funds as McKinley because his policies alienated Democratic donors who disagreed with his progressive policies.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Without much campaign funds to spend, Bryan could not extend his political outreach and only relied on himself to speak for his policies.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The financial disparity grew larger and larger as the Republicans funded more and more rallies, speeches, and torchlight parades, as well as hundreds of millions of pamphlets attacking Bryan and praising McKinley.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lacking a systematic fund-raising system, Bryan was unable to tap his potential supporters, and he had to rely on passing the hat at rallies.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Increasingly, the Republicans personalized their attacks on Bryan as a dangerous religious fanatic.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The counter-crusading rhetoric focused on Bryan as a reckless revolutionary whose policies would destroy the economic system.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Illinois Governor John Peter Altgeld was running for re-election after having pardoned several of the anarchists convicted in the Haymarket affair.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Republican posters and speeches linked Altgeld and Bryan as two dangerous anarchists.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican Party tried any number of tactics to ridicule Bryan's economic policies.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In one case they printed fake dollar bills which had Bryan's face and read "IN GOD WE TRUST ...
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] FOR THE OTHER 53 CENTS", illustrating their claim that a dollar bill would be worth only 47 cents if it was backed by silver instead of gold.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic Party in Eastern and Midwestern cities had a strong German Catholic base that was alienated by free silver and inflationist panaceas.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They showed little enthusiasm for Bryan, although many were worried that a Republican victory would bring prohibition into play.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Irish Catholics disliked Bryan's revivalistic rhetoric and worried about prohibition as well.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, their leaders decided to stick with Bryan, since the departure of so many Bourbon businessmen from the party left the Irish increasingly in control.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Bryan campaign appealed first of all to farmers.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It told urban workers that their return to prosperity was possible only if the farmers prospered first.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Among the industrial cities, Bryan carried only two (Troy, New York, and Fort Wayne, Indiana).
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The main labor unions were reluctant to endorse Bryan because their members feared inflation.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Railroad workers especially worried that Bryan's silver programs would bankrupt the railroads, which were in a shaky financial condition in the depression and whose bonds were payable in gold.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Factory workers saw no advantage in inflation to help miners and farmers, because their urban cost of living would shoot up and they would be hurt.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The McKinley campaign gave special attention to skilled workers, especially in the Midwest and adjacent states.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Secret polls show that large majorities of railroad and factory workers voted for McKinley.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Campaign strategies of both sides changed how candidates campaign in elections in the United States, shifting presidential campaigns to be more candidate-focused and reliant on campaign messaging to attract donors.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan's campaign was influential because of the populist messaging that Bryan presented in his speeches nationwide.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Even though Bryan did not have the same amount of campaign funds as McKinley, his messaging was impactful enough to earn a significant electoral vote, and he only needed a few more states to win the election.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McKinley's campaign was influential because of how he earned and used his campaign funds to undermine Bryan's campaign.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The front porch strategy was an excellent success for McKinley as he earned massive amounts of campaign funds from donors.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Additionally, the way McKinley used the funds to attack Bryan's campaign produced the intended effect of Americans viewing Bryan as a religious fanatic whose policies threatened to ruin the economy.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The outcome of the 1896 election shifted party coalitions as Republicans maintained strong relationships with businesses, professionals, skilled workers, and wealthy farmers.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Unfortunately for Democrats, they were not able to produce a coalition of lower-class farmers, unskilled laborers, and white southerners.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Throughout the campaign the South and Mountain states appeared certain to vote for Bryan, whereas the East was certain for McKinley.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In play were the Midwest and the Border States.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican Party amassed an unprecedented war chest at all levels: national, state and local.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Outspent and shut out of the party's traditional newspapers, Bryan decided his best chance to win the election was to conduct a vigorous national speaking tour by train.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His fiery crusading rhetoric to huge audiences would make his campaign a newsworthy story that the hostile press would have to cover, and he could speak to the voters directly instead of through editorials.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was the first presidential candidate since Stephen Douglas in 1860 to canvass directly, and the first ever to criss-cross the nation and meet voters in person.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The novelty of seeing a visiting presidential candidate, combined with Bryan's spellbinding oratory and the passion of his believers, generated huge crowds.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Silverites welcomed their hero with all-day celebrations of parades, band music, picnic meals, endless speeches, and undying demonstrations of support.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan focused his efforts on the Midwest, which everyone agreed would be the decisive battleground in the election.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In just 100 days, Bryan gave over 500 speeches to several million people.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His record was 36 speeches in one day in St.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Relying on just a few hours of sleep a night, he traveled 18,000 miles by rail to address five million people, often in a hoarse voice; he would explain that he left his real voice at the previous stops where it was still rallying the people.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In contrast to Bryan's dramatic efforts, McKinley conducted a "front porch" campaign from his home in Canton, Ohio.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Instead of having McKinley travel to see the voters, Mark Hanna brought 500,000 voters by train to McKinley's home.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Once there, McKinley would greet the men from his porch.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His well-organized staff prepared both the remarks of the visiting delegations and the candidate's responses, focusing the comments on the assigned topic of the day.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The remarks were issued to the newsmen and telegraphed nationwide to appear in the next day's papers.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan, with practically no staff, gave much the same talk over and over again.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McKinley labeled Bryan's proposed social and economic reforms as a serious threat to the national economy.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With the depression following the Panic of 1893 coming to an end, support for McKinley's more conservative economic policies increased, while Bryan's more radical policies began to lose support among Midwestern farmers and factory workers.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] To ensure victory, Hanna paid large numbers of Republican orators (including Theodore Roosevelt) to travel around the nation denouncing Bryan as a dangerous radical.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There were also reports that some potentially Democratic voters were intimidated into voting for McKinley.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] For example, some factory owners posted signs the day before the election announcing that, if Bryan won the election, the factory would be closed and the workers would lose their jobs.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan's midsummer surge in the Midwest played out as the intense Republican counter-crusade proved effective.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan spent most of October in the Midwest, making 160 of his final 250 speeches there.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Morgan noted, "full organization, Republican party harmony, a campaign of education with the printed and spoken word would more than counteract" Bryan's speechmaking.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Several of Bryan's advisors recommended additional campaigning in the Upper South States of Kentucky, West Virginia, Maryland and Delaware.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Another plan called for a coastal tour from Washington State to Southern California.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan however, opted to concentrate in the Mid-West and to launch a unity tour into the heavily Republican Northeast.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bryan saw no chance of winning in New England, but felt that he needed to make a truly national appeal.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On election day the results from the Pacific Coast and Upper South would be the closest of the election.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] 36.8% of the voting age population and 79.7% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] McKinley secured a solid victory in the electoral college by carrying the core of the East and Northeast, while Bryan did well among the farmers of the South, West, and rural Midwest.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The large German-American voting bloc supported McKinley, who gained a large majority among the middle class, skilled factory workers, railroad workers, and large-scale farmers.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the first time since 1876 that a candidate won a majority of the popular vote.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] 11.36% of McKinley's votes came from the eleven states of the former Confederacy, with him taking 35.30% of the vote in that region.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the first time a Republican presidential candidate had ever carried Kentucky, but they did not do so again until Calvin Coolidge in 1924.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] From this, they concluded that Palmer had siphoned off needed Democratic votes and hence thrown the state to McKinley.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, McKinley would have won the overall election even if he had lost Kentucky to Bryan.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A 2022 study found that campaign visits by Bryan increased his vote share by one percentage point on average.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] McKinley received a little more than seven million votes, Bryan a little less than six and a half million, about 800,000 in excess of the Democratic vote in 1892.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was larger than the Democratic Party was to poll in 1900, 1904, or 1912.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was somewhat less, however, than the combined vote for the Democratic and Populist nominees had been in 1892.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In contrast, McKinley received nearly 2,000,000 more votes than had been cast for Benjamin Harrison, the Republican nominee, in 1892.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Republican vote was to be slightly increased during the next decade.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As of 2024, this is the last occasion Northampton County North Carolina has voted for a Republican presidential candidate, which stands as the longest Democratic streak in the nation.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The 1896 presidential election is often seen as a realigning election, in which McKinley's view of a stronger central government building American industry through protective tariffs and a dollar based on gold triumphed.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The new Fourth Party System then displaced the near-deadlock in the Third Party System since the Civil War.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Republicans now usually dominated in the major states and nationwide down to the 1932 election, another realigning election with the ascent of Franklin Roosevelt and the Fifth Party System.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Phillips argues that McKinley was the only Republican who could have defeated Bryan—he concludes that Eastern candidates would have done badly against the Illinois-born Bryan in the crucial Midwest.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] One-half of the total vote of the nation was polled in eight states carried by McKinley (New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, and Wisconsin).
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In these states, Bryan not only ran far behind the Republican candidate, but also polled considerably less than half of his total vote.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bryan only won in twelve of the eighty-two cities in the United States with populations above 45,000 with seven of those being in the Solid South.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the states that Bryan won, seven of the seventeen cities voted for McKinley while in the states that voted for McKinley only three of the sixty-five cities voted for Bryan.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bryan lost in every county in New England and only won one county in New York, with Bryan even losing in traditionally Democratic New York City, which had last failed to support a Democratic nominee in 1848.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In only one other section, in the six states of New England, was the Republican lead great; the Republican vote (614,972) was more than twice the Democratic vote (242,938), and every county was carried by the Republicans.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The West North Central section gave a slight lead to McKinley, as did the Pacific section.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nevertheless, within these sections, the states of Missouri, South Dakota, Nebraska, Kansas, and Washington were carried by Bryan.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the South Atlantic section and in the East South Central section, the Democratic lead was pronounced, and in the West South Central section and in the Mountain section, the vote for Bryan was overwhelming.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In these four sections, comprising 21 states, McKinley carried only 322 counties and four states – Delaware, Maryland, West Virginia, and Kentucky.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A striking feature of this examination of the state returns is found in the overwhelming lead for one or the other party in 22 of the 45 states.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was true of the McKinley vote in every New England state and in New York, Pennsylvania, and Illinois.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was also true of the Bryan vote in eight states of the lower South and five states of the Mountain West.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Sectionalism was thus marked in this first election of the Fourth Party System.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the last election in which the Democrats won South Dakota until 1932, the last in which the Democrats won Utah and Washington until 1916, and the last in which the Democrats won Kansas and Wyoming until 1912.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was also the last time that South Dakota and Washington voted against the Republicans until they voted for the Progressive Party in 1912.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This also constitutes the only election since their statehoods when a Republican won the presidency without winning Kansas, South Dakota, Utah, or Wyoming.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Today these are solidly Republican states and have not backed a Democratic nominee since Lyndon Johnson's 1964 landslide over Barry Goldwater.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is one of two occasions where Idaho and Montana backed a losing Democrat (along with 1900), and one of two occasions where Nebraska did so (along with 1908).
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the first occasion where Republicans won without Colorado.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Even in Georgia, a state in the Deep South, there were counties returning Republican majorities.
[src:canton-ohio/1896-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election parade for William McKinley is seen in the 1952 film adaptation of *The Little House*.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Founded in 1805 alongside Nimishillen Creek, Canton became a center of heavy industry because of its numerous railroad lines.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] As shifts in the manufacturing industry led to the relocation or downsizing of many factories and workers during the late 20th century, the city's industry diversified into the service economy, including retailing, education, finance and healthcare.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is best known as the home of the Pro Football Hall of Fame and the birthplace of the National Football League.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] 25th U.S. president William McKinley conducted his famous front porch campaign from his home in Canton, winning the presidency in the 1896 election.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The McKinley National Memorial and William McKinley Presidential Library and Museum commemorate his life and presidency.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton was also selected as the site of the First Ladies National Historic Site largely in honor of his wife, Ida Saxton McKinley.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Its plat was recorded at New Lisbon, Ohio, on November 15, 1805, by surveyor Bezaleel Wells, who later served in the Ohio Senate.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton was likely named as a memorial to Captain John O'Donnell, an Irish merchant marine with the British East India Company whom Wells admired.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] O'Donnell named his estate in Maryland after the Chinese port city of Guangzhou, formerly romanized as Canton.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] O'Donnell was the first person to transport goods from Guangzhou to Baltimore.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The name selected by Wells may also have been influenced by the Huguenot use of the word "canton", which meant a division of a district containing several communes.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Through Wells' efforts and promotion, Canton was designated the county seat of Stark County upon its division from Columbiana County on January 1, 1809.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton was incorporated as a village in 1822 and reincorporated as a city in 1838.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Wells donated his personal holdings in the city to Canton; these holdings would become the Christ United Presbyterian Church, Timken Vocational High School and McKinley Park (originally a cemetery).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] For most of his adult life, Canton was the home of William McKinley, the 25th president of the United States.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Born in Niles, Ohio, McKinley first practiced law in Canton around 1867 and was prosecuting attorney of Stark County from 1869 to 1871.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The city was his home during his successful campaign for Ohio governor, the site of his front-porch presidential campaign of 1896 and the campaign of 1900.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is now the site of the William McKinley Presidential Library and Museum and the McKinley National Memorial, dedicated in 1907.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] President McKinley's impact on Canton as his adopted home is still reflected today in many different ways, and he remains the namesake of McKinley Senior High School of the Canton City School System.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Debs delivered the keynote speech at the annual Ohio Socialist Convention held in Canton's Nimisilla Park.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] At the time, Debs had been a four-time candidate for president and was considered the country's leading socialist and labor organizer.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] During his speech he decried America's involvement in the First World War, saying, "They have always taught you that it is your patriotic duty to go to war and slaughter yourselves at their command.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The working class who make the sacrifices, who shed the blood, have never yet had a voice in declaring war." Among Debs' audience at Nimisilla Park were agents of the U.S.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Debs' trial began on September 10, 1918, in the U.S.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] District Court for the Northern District of Ohio.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] On September 12, 1918, a jury found Debs guilty.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] He was sentenced to ten years in prison.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Supreme Court affirmed the constitutionality of Debs' conviction in *Debs v.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Debs began serving his prison sentence on April 13, 1919, and remained incarcerated until December 25, 1921, when he was released after President Warren Harding commuted his sentence to time served.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Supreme Court's decision affirming Debs' conviction was sharply criticized by legal scholars at the time and is generally regarded as a low point in First Amendment jurisprudence.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The lead author of the opinion, progressive Supreme Court Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes, later changed course that same term and authored a dissenting opinion recognizing the constitutional protection of such speech in *Abrams v.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Brandeis was the only other jurist to join Justice Holmes' dissent, and the minority opinion had no effect on Debs' conviction and continued incarceration.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The changed mind articulated by Justice Holmes on November 10, 1919, nevertheless had a profound impact on the development of American constitutional law.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] His dissent in *Abrams* is considered by many legal scholars to be the canonical affirmation of free speech in the United States.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] While Debs' speech in Canton and subsequent conviction ultimately aided Debs in delivering the Socialist Party's antiwar platform, his age and the deleterious effects of prison exhausted his ability as an orator.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Debs died of heart failure on October 20, 1926.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] His obituary in *The New York Times* recounted his words from the Ohio federal courtroom: "At his trial he admitted the charges against him, declaring he would not retract a word he had uttered to save himself from going to the penitentiary for the rest of his days.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In June 2017 Canton applied for and received a historical marker from the Ohio History Connection, formerly the Ohio Historical Society.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The marker is located next to where Debs stood in Canton on the afternoon of June 16, 1918.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] It commemorates the significance and legacy of his speech at Nimisilla Park, notes the many speeches at the park by other prominent historical figures, and honors the park's continued importance as a gathering place for the community.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Timken Company has been among the largest employers in Canton for nearly 100 years.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In 1898, Henry Timken obtained a patent for the tapered roller bearing, and in 1899 incorporated as the Timken Roller Bearing Axle Company in St.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In 1901, the company moved to Canton as the automobile industry began to overtake the carriage industry.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Timken and his two sons chose this location because of its proximity to the American car manufacturing centers of Detroit and Cleveland and the American steel-making centers of Pittsburgh and Cleveland.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] By 1960, Timken had operations in the U.S., Canada, Great Britain, France, South Africa, Australia and Brazil.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The company changed its corporate structure in 2014; the roller bearing-producing part of the company was separated from the steel-producing part of the company, resulting in two separate companies.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Timken Company continues to manufacture roller bearings, while TimkenSteel produces steel.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Today, TimkenSteel remains headquartered in Canton and employs 2,800 people, most of them in Northeast Ohio.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The company makes special bar quality steel, used in applications all over the world.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Timken Co. is now headquartered in Jackson Township, a suburb of Canton, and employs 14,000 people around the world.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The company designs, engineers, manufactures and sells bearings, transmissions, gearboxes, chain and related products, and offers a spectrum of power system rebuild and repair services around the globe.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Dueber-Hampden Watch Company was an important employer in Canton during the early 1920s.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] It was formally organized in 1923, having previously consisted of two separate companies: the Dueber Watch Case Company and the Hampden Watch Company.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In 1886, John Dueber, the owner of the Dueber Watch Case Company, purchased a controlling interest in the Hampden Watch Company.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In 1888, he relocated the Hampden Watch Company from Springfield, Massachusetts and the Dueber Watch Case Company from Newport, Kentucky to Canton, Ohio.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] These two companies shared manufacturing facilities in Canton but remained two separate companies.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Dueber Watch Case Company and the Hampden Watch Company quickly became two of Canton's largest employers.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In 1888, the companies' first year in Canton, they employed 2,300 Canton residents.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Thanks to these two companies, Canton became an important center for watch manufacturing in the United States.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In 1927 the company went bankrupt, finally ceasing operations in the city in 1930.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The machinery and tools were sold to the Amtorg Trading Corporation, one of Soviet Russia's buying agencies in the US, for $329.000.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The company's massive brick factories, which covered over 20 acres and included an ornate 150-foot clock tower, were demolished to accommodate the construction of Interstate 77.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] On September 17, 1920, a meeting was held at the Hupmobile showroom in the Independent Order of Odd Fellows Building in Canton to found the American Professional Football Association (renamed the National Football League in 1922).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The attendees included Ralph Hay, owner of the Hupmobile showroom and the hometown Canton Bulldogs, and George Halas, owner of the Decatur Staleys.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Jim Thorpe of the Bulldogs was the league's first president.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In 2014 a sculpture titled *Birth of the NFL* was erected in downtown Canton marking the exact location in the Hupmobile showroom where the NFL was created in 1920.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] On December 6, 1959, the *Canton Repository*, a local newspaper, called for city officials to lobby the National Football League to create a football hall of fame in the community.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton officials formally proposed their city as the site for the Hall of Fame in 1961.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The NFL quickly agreed to the city's proposal.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] To help convince NFL officials to locate the Hall of Fame in Canton, city officials donated several acres of land on Canton's north side to the project.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Local residents also raised almost $400,000 to help construct the Hall of Fame.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Pro Football Hall of Fame formally opened on September 7, 1963.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Initially, the museum consisted of two buildings, but in 1971, 1978, 1995, and 2013, the Pro Football Hall of Fame experienced several expansions.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] As of 2013, the museum consisted of five buildings, covering 118,000 square feet.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Since its founding, over 10 million people have visited the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] "Welcome to Canton" is the official way of saying congratulations to a new enshrinee.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Starting in the mid-2010s, Canton began experiencing an urban renaissance, anchored by a growing arts district centrally located in the downtown area.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Several historic buildings have been rehabilitated and converted into upscale lofts, attracting hundreds of new downtown residents into the city.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Furthering this downtown development, in June 2016, Canton became one of the first cities in Ohio to allow the open consumption of alcoholic beverages in a "designated outdoor refreshment area" pursuant to a state law enacted in 2015.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is located at an elevation of 1,060 feet (323 m).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Nimishillen Creek and its East, Middle and West Branches flow through the city.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is bordered by Plain Township and North Canton to the north, Meyers Lake and Perry Township to the west, Canton Township to the South, and Nimishillen Township, Osnaburg Township and East Canton to the east.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Annexations were approved in December 2006 extending Canton's eastern boundary to East Canton's border.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 26.327 square miles (68.19 km2), of which 26.309 square miles (68.14 km2) is land and 0.018 square miles (0.047 km2) (0.07%) is water.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton has a humid continental climate (Köppen climate classification *Dfa*), typical of much of the Midwestern United States, with warm, humid summers and cold winters.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Winters tend to be cold, with average January high temperatures of 34 °F (1 °C), and average lows of 19 °F (−7 °C), with considerable variation in temperatures.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] During a typical January, high temperatures of over 50 °F (10 °C) are just as common as low temperatures of below 0 °F (−18 °C).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Snowfall is lighter than the snow belt areas to the north.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Akron-Canton Airport generally averages 47.7 inches (121 cm) of snow per season.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Springs are short with rapid transition from hard winter to summer weather.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Summers tend to be warm, sometimes hot, with average July high temperatures of 83 °F (28 °C), and average July low of 62 °F (17 °C).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Summer weather is more stable, generally humid with thunderstorms fairly common.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Temperatures reach or exceed 90 °F (32 °C) about 10 times each summer, on average.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Fall usually is the driest season with many clear, warm days and cool nights.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The all-time record high in the Akron-Canton area of 104 °F (40 °C) was established on August 6, 1918, and the all-time record low of −25 °F (−32 °C) was set on January 19, 1994.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton's street layout forms the basis for the system of addresses in Stark County.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton proper is divided into address quadrants (NW, NE, SW, SE) by Tuscarawas Street (dividing N and S) and Market Avenue (dividing E and W).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Due to shifts in the street layout, the E–W divider becomes Cleveland Avenue south of the city, merging onto Ridge Road farther out.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The directionals are noted as suffixes to the street name (e.g.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Typically within the city numbered streets run east and west and radiate from the Tuscarawas Street baseline, while named avenues run north and south.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Ridgewood Historic District is a historic residential neighborhood in Canton that, due to its architectural significance, was added to the U.S.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] National Register of Historic Places on December 19, 1982.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The neighborhood consists of preserved, architect-designed Revival style buildings of the Tudor, Georgian, and French-Norman styles built in the early 20th century with amenities such as original brick streets and locally produced street lighting standards.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The District features homes designed by several distinguished architects, including Charles Firestone, Herman Albrecht, and Louis Hoicowitz.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] According to realtor website Zillow, the average price of a home as of November 30, 2025, in Canton is $164,993.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] As of the 2024 American Community Survey, there are 28,487 estimated households in Canton with an average of 2.36 persons per household.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The city has a median household income of $46,320.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Approximately 32.2% of the city's population lives at or below the poverty line.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton has an estimated 56.0% employment rate, with 16.7% of the population holding a bachelor's degree or higher and 90.1% holding a high school diploma.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] There were 32,425 housing units at an average density of 1,232.47 per square mile (475.9/km2).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The median age in the city was 32.9 years.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] As of the 2024 estimate, there were 69,211 people, 28,487 households, and _ families residing in the city.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The population density was 2,630.70 inhabitants per square mile (1,015.7/km2).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The racial makeup of the city was 62.1% White *(60.1% NH White)*, 24.7% African American, 0.1% Native American, 0.5% Asian, 0.2% Pacific Islander, _% from some other races and 11.4% from two or more races.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 6.3% of the population.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] As of the 2020 census, there were 70,872 people, 29,959 households, and 16,239 families residing in the city.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The median age was 36.5 years; 24.3% of residents were under the age of 18 and 15.5% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] For every 100 females there were 92.1 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 88.1 males age 18 and over.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] 99.9% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Of the 29,959 households in Canton, 27.5% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Of all households, 26.1% were married-couple households, 24.9% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 39.1% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] About 38.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] There were 33,587 housing units, of which 10.8% were vacant.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Among occupied housing units, 46.2% were owner-occupied and 53.8% were renter-occupied.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.2% and the rental vacancy rate was 8.7%.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] As of the 2010 census, there were 73,007 people, 29,705 households, and 17,127 families residing in the city.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The population density was 2,867.52 inhabitants per square mile (1,107.2/km2).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] There were 34,571 housing units at an average density of 1,357.86 per square mile (524.3/km2).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The racial makeup of the city was 69.11% White, 24.20% African American, 0.48% Native American, 0.35% Asian, 0.05% Pacific Islander, 1.01% from some other races and 4.81% from two or more races.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 2.60% of the population.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] There were 29,705 households, of which 31.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 30.8% were married couples living together, 21.1% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 42.3% were non-families.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] 35.4% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The average household size was 2.35 and the average family size was 3.04.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The median age in the city was 35.6 years.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] 25.1% of residents were under the age of 18; 10.8% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 25.6% were from 25 to 44; 25.6% were from 45 to 64; and 12.8% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The gender makeup of the city was 47.4% male and 52.6% female.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] As of the 2000 census, there were 80,806 people, 32,489 households, and 19,785 families residing in the city.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The population density was 3,933.00 inhabitants per square mile (1,518.5/km2).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] There were 35,502 housing units at an average density of 1,727.96 per square mile (667.2/km2).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The racial makeup of the city was 74.45% White, 21.04% African American, 0.49% Native American, 0.32% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, 0.61% from some other races and 3.06% from two or more races.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 1.24% of the population.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] There were 32,489 households, out of which 30.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 37.1% were married couples living together, 19.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 39.1% were non-families.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] 33.0% of all households were made up of individuals, and 12.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The average household size was 2.39 and the average family size was 3.04.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In the city the age distribution of the population shows 26.6% under the age of 18, 9.8% from 18 to 24, 29.1% from 25 to 44, 20.2% from 45 to 64, and 14.3% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] For every 100 females, there were 87.5 males.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 81.9 males.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The median income for a household in the city was $28,730, and the median income for a family was $35,680.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Males had a median income of $30.628 versus $21,581 for females.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The per capita income for the city was $15,544.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] About 15.4% of families and 19.2% of the population were below the poverty line, including 27.4% of those under age 18 and 11.3% of those age 65 or over.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton's economy has traditionally been primarily industrial, with significant healthcare and agricultural segments.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The city is home to the TimkenSteel Corporation, a major manufacturer of specialty steel.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The area is also home to several regional food producers, including Nickles Bakery (baked goods), Case Farms (poultry), and Shearer's Foods (snack foods).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Poultry production and dairy farming are also important segments of the Canton area's economy.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Since 2000, Canton has experienced a very low unemployment rate.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The healthcare sector is particularly strong, with Aultman Hospital and Mercy Medical Center among its largest employers.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Nevertheless, as in many industrial areas of the United States, employment in the manufacturing sector is in a state of decline.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] LTV Steel (formerly Republic Steel) suffered bankruptcy in 2000.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Republic Steel emerged and continues to maintain operations in Canton.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Hoover Company, a major employer for decades in the region, reached an agreement to sell Hoover to Hong Kong-based Techtronic Industries.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The main plant in nearby North Canton closed its doors in September 2007 due to classified reasons.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] On June 30, 2014, the Timken Company and TimkenSteel split, forming two separate companies at the urging of shareholders.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Timken Company relocated to neighboring Jackson Township, while TimkenSteel remains headquartered in Canton.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In response to this changing manufacturing landscape, the city is undergoing a transition to a retail and service-based economy.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Beginning in the 1970s, Canton, like many mid-size American cities, lost most of its downtown retail business to the suburbs.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The majority of the Canton area's "box store" retail is located in the general vicinity of the Belden Village Mall in Jackson Township.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] However, the 2010s saw the downtown area bringing in new cafes, restaurants, and the establishment of an arts district.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] A few retail centers remain in Canton at or near the city limits.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Tuscarawas Street (Lincoln Way), a leg of the Lincoln Highway connecting Canton with nearby Massillon, is home to the Canton Centre mall and several retail outlets of varying size.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] A vein of commerce runs along Whipple Avenue, connecting the Canton Centre area with the Belden Village area.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] A similar vein runs north from the downtown area, along Cleveland and Market avenues.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Connecting Cleveland and Market avenues is a small shopping district on 30th Street NW, and retail lines the Route 62 corridor leading from Canton to Louisville and Alliance.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The city's economy has diversified due to the decline of the heavy manufacturing industry.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] At the heart of this transformation is the Pro Football Hall of Fame, with its multimillion-dollar "Hall of Fame Village" expansion project.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] This project has been complemented with significant investments by city leaders in urban redevelopment, which continued with the transformation of the Hotel Onesto into the Historic Onesto Lofts.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Other urban renewal plans are underway, which include the redevelopment of the downtown Market Square area.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Private investment has furthered Canton's transformation, which is illustrated by the multimillion-dollar creation of the Gervasi Vineyard, which draws patrons throughout the region.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In furtherance of these development initiatives, Canton was one of the first cities in Ohio to create a "designated outdoor refreshment area" legalizing the possession and consumption of "open container" alcoholic beverages in its downtown area.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Canton Museum of Art, founded in 1935, is a broad-based community arts organization designed to encourage and promote the fine arts in Canton.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The museum focuses on 19th- and 20th-century American artists, specifically works on paper, and on American ceramics, beginning in the 1950s.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The museum sponsors annual shows of the work of high school students in Canton and Stark County, and financial scholarships are awarded.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Educational outreach programs take the museum off-site to libraries, parochial schools, area public schools, five inner-city schools, and a school for students with behavioral disorders.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The city's Arts District, located downtown, is the site of monthly First Friday arts celebrations.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton has the main branch of Stark County District Library.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is home to the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The American Professional Football Association, the forerunner of the modern National Football League, was founded in a Canton car dealership on September 17, 1920.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Canton Bulldogs were an NFL football team that played from 1920 to 1923, skipped the 1924 season, then played from 1925 to 1926 before folding.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is the home of the annual Pro Football Hall of Fame Enshrinement Festival, which includes a hot air balloon festival, ribs burn-off, fashion show, community parade, Sunday morning race, enshrinee dinner, and the Pro Football Hall of Fame Grand Parade.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The festival culminates in the enshrinement of the new inductees and the NFL/Hall of Fame Game, a pre-season exhibition between teams representing the AFC and NFC at Tom Benson Hall of Fame Stadium.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Tom Benson Hall of Fame Stadium, used during the regular season by Canton McKinley High School (as well as some other area schools and colleges), was rated the number one high school football venue in America by the *Sporting News* in 2002.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] This may be partly attributable to the Bulldogs' rivalry with the nearby Massillon Washington High School Tigers.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] All seven of the Ohio High School Athletic Association state final football games are hosted in Canton at Tom Benson Hall of Fame Stadium.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Canton Legends played in the American Indoor Football Association at the Canton Civic Center.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Continental Indoor Football League also has offices in Canton.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] For the 2023 United States Football League (USFL) season, Canton served as the hub for the New Jersey Generals and Pittsburgh Maulers, with both teams playing their designated home games at Tom Benson Hall of Fame Stadium.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The first official female bodybuilding competition was held in Canton in November 1977 and was called the Ohio Regional Women's Physique Championship.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] For 10 seasons, Canton was home to an NBA G League team, the Canton Charge, which started play with the 2011–12 season and home games at the Canton Memorial Civic Center.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Cleveland Cavaliers had full control over the franchise and relocated the franchise in to Cleveland in 2021 when the ten-year lease ended.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Canton Invaders of the National Professional Soccer League II and American Indoor Soccer Association played home games at the Canton Memorial Civic Center from 1984 until 1996, winning five league championships.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In 2009, the Ohio Vortex became an expansion team in the Professional Arena Soccer League.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton has been home to professional baseball on several occasions.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Several minor league teams called Canton home in the early 1900s, including the Canton Terriers in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Canton–Akron Indians were the AA affiliate of the major league Cleveland Indians for nine years, playing at Thurman Munson Memorial Stadium until the team relocated north to Akron following the 1996 season.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Two independent minor league teams, the Canton Crocodiles and the Canton Coyotes, both members of the Frontier League, called Munson Stadium home for several years afterward.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The Crocodiles, who won the league championship in their inaugural season in 1997, moved to Washington, Pennsylvania, in 2002, and the Coyotes moved to Columbia, Missouri, in 2003, after just one season in Canton.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is home to the Bluecoats Drum and Bugle Corps, a world-class competitor in Drum Corps International.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton has a mayor–council government and is the largest city in Ohio to operate without a charter.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The city council is divided among nine wards with three at-large seats and the council president.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In addition, an independently elected mayor serves as an executive.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Sherer II and the council president is Kristen Bates Aylward.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is included in Ohio's 29th senatorial district, represented by Jane Timken, and the 49th district of the Ohio House of Representatives, represented by Jim Thomas.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] At the federal level, it has been included in Ohio's 13th congressional district since 2022 and is represented by Emilia Sykes.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In April 2024, officers of the Canton Police Department restrained 53-year-old Frank Tyson after a car crash, with Tyson dying after the restraint.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Police took down Tyson to the ground, handcuffed him, and then one officer kneeled on Tyson for roughly 30 seconds, with Tyson stating: "I can't breathe.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] After the knee was removed and Tyson was left on his stomach, Tyson became motionless and subsequently died.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Two Canton officers were assigned paid administrative leave during an investigation into the incident.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In May 2024, Canton Police officers arrested a male bystander during a traffic stop after Patrolman Nicholas Casto accused him of taunting his police dog.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Body camera footage showed several officers bringing the bystander to the ground, and Casto leading the dog to bite his arm for 15 seconds, despite the bystander keeping his arms still.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] After the dog was removed, Casto praised it.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Casto was placed on paid administrative leave, prompting concern from Canton councilmen.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In early June, Police Chief John Gabbard recommended Casto's dismissal for false statements in his report that justified excessive force.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Director Andrea Perry, supported by Mayor William Sherer, fired Casto in late June, concluding the bystander posed no threat and Casto's actions endangered officers.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Perry confirmed Casto knowingly provided inaccurate information.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton's K-12 students are primarily served by the public Canton City School District, which included eight elementary schools, three middle schools, and two high schools, in addition to alternative education centers.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] A portion of northern Canton is included in the Plain Local School District, and another overlap exists with the suburban Canton Local School District.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Catholic grade schools within Canton are St.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Additional Catholic schools in the immediate area include St.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Michael the Archangel School (PK–8) and Central Catholic High School (9–12).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] There is also Heritage Christian School (K–12), a Christian grade school and high school.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton Country Day School is a private PreK–8 school located just outside city limits founded as part of the Country Day School movement.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Within the city limits is the private Canton Montessori School, which teaches according to the Montessori Plan for Education proposed by Maria Montessori in the early 20th century.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Malone University, a private, four-year liberal arts college affiliated with the Evangelical Friends Church - Eastern Region, is located on 25th Street NW.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Catholic-run Walsh University is located nearby in North Canton.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Stark State College and a branch of Kent State University are also nearby in Jackson Township.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Also in downtown Canton, there is a small annex for Stark State College to be used by the early college high school students who are located on the Timken Campus.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is served in print by *The Repository*, the city's only newspaper.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is part of the Cleveland/Akron/Canton television media market.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Four stations are licensed to Canton – full-power WDLI (Bounce) and WRLM (TCT), and low-power WOHZ-CD (RESN) and WIVM-LD (Independent).
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The two full-power stations identify as *Canton/Akron/Cleveland*, serving the entire market, while the two low-power stations specifically serve Canton.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton also has a cable Public-access television channel, Canton City Schools TV 11.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] The content varies based on the viewer's location.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Citizens located in North Canton will see North Canton's programming instead of Canton City's.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Those within the borders of Plain Local Schools will see Eagle Television's programming.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Canton is connected to the Interstate Highway System via Interstate 77, which connects Canton to Marietta to the south and Cleveland to the north.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Route 30 connects Canton to Wooster westward and East Liverpool eastward.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Route 62 connects Canton to Millersburg to the southwest and to Youngstown to the northeast.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Until 1990, Amtrak's passenger trains *Broadway Limited* and the *Capitol Limited* made stops at Canton station.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Amtrak's *Capitol Limited* currently makes stops in Alliance station, 20 miles (32 km) to the northeast.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Norfolk Southern and the Wheeling and Lake Erie railroads provide freight service in Canton.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] Stark Area Regional Transit Authority (SARTA) provides public transit bus service within the county, including service to Massillon and the Akron-Canton Regional Airport.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In February 2022, it was reported that SARTA had hired a consultant group to study the feasibility of a light rail line from the Pro Football Hall of Fame to downtown Canton, with possible expansion to other locations around the county in the future.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] In June of that same year, the full plan was released, calling for a nine-mile line from Akron-Canton Airport to downtown, where it would run down 3rd street in a separated lane from traffic.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] It would connect to existing bus services near Belden Village Mall and Cornerstone Transit Center.
[src:canton-ohio/canton-ohio] A first round of public meetings was held.
